subsystem-promote-and-daemon-guard.value:
Two patterns from PR #112 (always-on scheduling infra, Phase 1):

(1) Subsystem promotion: when a subsystem initially housed under one feature (e.g. src/dashboard/scheduler.js) grows to serve the whole mesh, relocate it to a dedicated module (e.g. src/schedule/). Use `git mv` — behavior-preserving; repoint all importers and test imports. The old path becomes dead code the moment importers are updated; do not leave it in place. Applies to: any service initially placed under a feature dir that becomes cross-cutting infrastructure.

(2) Always-on daemon guard: a daemon that starts long-running services must guard against single-pass modes:
```
if (!opts.once && !opts.selftest) {
  const svc = createService(meshRoot);
  svc.start();
  process.on('SIGTERM', () => svc.stop());
  process.on('SIGINT',  () => svc.stop());
}
```
Why: --once and --selftest are sweep/health-check invocations that must complete and exit. A scheduler or background poller started in those modes outlives the sweep, leaks process resources, and interferes with subsequent test runs.

Test coverage: (a) selftest mode → service.start() is NOT called, process exits 0; (b) normal mode → service.start() called, SIGTERM triggers stop(). See test/daemon-scheduler.test.js (PR #112).

(3) Read-only aggregation API: expose per-agent state as a mesh-wide read-only endpoint (GET /api/schedules → {schedulerOwner, jobs:[...]}). The endpoint is a view, not a store — data lives in per-agent files. Use injected deps for hermetic testing. Provenance: PR #112 (2026-06-18).

gha-cron-throttle-use-daemon-builtin.value:
When a sweep must complete within minutes, not hours:

(1) Register a daemon builtin in the target agent's schedule.json: {"id": "automerge-sweep", "kind": "builtin", "name": "automerge-sweep", "enabled": true, "every": 10}. The daemon scheduler dispatches by kind — no LLM spawn.

(2) Register the function in the daemon's builtin registry (scripts/dev-society-daemon.mjs):
  builtins['automerge-sweep'] = async () => {
    if (!enabled) return {status:'ok', output:'disabled'};
    await runAutomergeSweep({...});
    return {status:'ok'};
  };
Gate on the sweep's kill-switch env var (AUTOMERGE_ENABLED). Return {status:'ok'} explicitly — void breaks onJobResult (see scheduler-builtin-return-shape).

(3) Keep the GHA cron workflow as a cold-start backstop. Share the same runSweep/isAutoMergeable logic — no duplication between daemon and GHA paths.

(4) Test: assert (a) daemon registers the builtin name; (b) builtin gates on the env flag; (c) schedule.json has the job at every ≤10; (d) existing GHA cron schedule remains present.

Red flag: PRs idle for hours while the automerge workflow claims `*/15` → GHA cron is throttled; migrate sweep to daemon builtin. Provenance: PR #231 (2026-06-20).

gitignored-generated-file-absent-test.value:
Pattern: testing doctor-generated / tool-generated files that are gitignored.

(1) NEVER assert 'file must not exist'. Gitignored files are absent on clean CI clones but present on deployed instances where the generator ran. Result: CI=green, production=red (env-flaky).

(2) Assert the REAL invariant: IF the file exists, it must match the expected schema/content:
  if (existsSync(path)) {
    const cfg = JSON.parse(readFileSync(path, 'utf8'));
    // e.g. assert only the ask-safe peer-bridge is present; no mutating servers
    assert.ok(cfg.mcpServers?.agentmesh_peerbridge);
    assert.strictEqual(Object.keys(cfg.mcpServers).length, 1);
  }
  // No else — absence is vacuously correct

(3) The stated invariant is almost never 'file must not exist' — it is a safety property about the file's CONTENTS (e.g. 'no mutating servers', 'only ask-safe bridge'). Test that.

(4) Env-flaky signature: test passes in hermetic CI (npm test) but fails under MIR --run-suites (real deploy). Primary suspect: an absence assertion on a gitignored, generator-produced artifact.

(5) When fixing one such test, audit sibling gitignored files (*.mcp.json, .agent/*.json) for the same pattern — absence tests cluster around framework-generated artifacts.

Provenance: PR #300 (2026-06-21).

mir-rolling-window-median-baseline.value:
Apply when adding baseline comparison to any time-series metric with high coefficient of variation (CV > ~0.3) — typically ratio metrics like cost-per-turn, tokens-per-run, latency-per-token.

(1) Carry history per finding: in the baseline record (mir.json), append the current metric value to the per-finding `history` array, capped to `trendN` entries:
  newHistory[f.id] = [...priorValues, f.metric.value].slice(-trendN);

(2) Two-tier baseline selection:
  if (priorValues.length >= MEDIAN_WINDOW_MIN) {  // 3 is the Phase-0 constant
    base = median(priorValues.slice(-trendN));     // outlier-resistant
  } else {
    base = prevFindings.get(f.id)?.metric.value;   // cold-start fallback
  }

(3) Why median over mean: a single anomalous run (network latency, model jitter) inflates the mean and triggers a false regression alarm on the next normal run. Median is insensitive to a single outlier in a window of trendN. Heuristic: if σ/mean > 0.3, single-previous-value is too noisy — switch to median.

(4) Cold-start invariant: MEDIAN_WINDOW_MIN = 3 means runs 1 and 2 always use §10 single-previous. Never compute a median on fewer than 3 points; the result would be less stable than the value itself.

(5) Spec-conformance guard: when an implementation decision was previously deferred, lock it with a test that reads both the spec and the code:
  const spec = readFileSync('docs/.../design.md', 'utf8');
  assert.ok(!spec.includes('v2-deferred'), '§11 must be in v1');
  const code = readFileSync('src/.../baseline.js', 'utf8');
  assert.ok(code.includes('median('), 'median must be in baseline.js');
A future PR re-deferring the feature must also update the spec — CI enforces the coupling.

(6) Required test matrix: cold-start fallback, median smoothing (outlier suppression), real regression detection (genuine δ), outlier recovery (metric returns to normal), history GC (trendN eviction), spec-conformance guard. Without all six, a refactor can silently remove cold-start safety or windowing.

Provenance: PR #330 (2026-06-21), closes #324.
